Yes — Claude and ChatGPT are both LLMs (Large Language Models) — AI systems trained on massive text datasets to understand and generate
human-like language. Claude is made by Anthropic, ChatGPT by OpenAI. Different companies, different training data/approach, but same 
underlying category of technology.

Can you create your own LLM? Depends what you mean by "own":

| Approach                          | What it means                                                                          | Feasibility for you                                                                                          |
|-----------------------------------|-----------------------------------------------------------------------|-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| Train from scratch                | Build a transformer architecture, train on billions of tokens                         | Not realistic solo — needs massive compute (thousands of GPUs, millions of $), datasets, months of training   |
| Fine-tune an existing open model  | Take an open-source model (Llama, Mistral, Phi) and train it further on your own data | Realistic — can be done on a decent GPU or cloud instance, even a single RTX 4090 or cloud A100               |
| RAG (Retrieval-Augmented Generation) | Keep the base model as-is, but feed it your own documents/data at query time       | Easiest — no training needed at all, just embeddings + a vector DB                                            |
| Run a local open-source model     | Download Llama/Mistral and run it locally via tools like Ollama                       | Very realistic — runs on your own laptop today                                                                |


Honest expectation-setting: You won't match Claude's or ChatGPT's quality — those are trained on massive infrastructure you can't 
replicate solo. But you can build a working, private, personalized assistant that's genuinely useful for your own notes/workflow.

